<subSubSection id="60AA658906B4E807281C718F71F38C61" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="857C9346CFC12C4E148F56CF2BB37F09" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3666935F974D8E919D8F41B1C3D084A0" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Shell elongated conical. Penis simple, broad at the basis and tapered at the distal end, with a black pigmentation mark. The tentacles are cylindrical.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44977ACCAEDB04F6772769CE6DE4CD5E" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="type species">
<paragraph id="03BAD51AE097CE91F6646F8B9D4BBFC6" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B11458998A7C3A81A3173DDF3746F230" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="1B7401A53D146539544F36A16AFC6111" genus="Sarkia" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="sarabensis">
<emphasis id="DCB51058711A6CD7DD068750C112646F" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Sarkia sarabensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ACA4822D348E6C4F7D190ED01BE122F5" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6AB64B00E808D65C56E2C15EEABD7926" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5236D3F73872BA91D7FDF4F5C6232844" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Named after the region where the species was collected.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="26DBAA5E5277D7FF0E0D11EC63C6B5E4" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="429944DBF93D62438C9A2D41F4789FB6" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="66E74DD6C122D937130616008334BD55" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
The genus seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="8B72DFCFD87A439F649223F732C1D8FF" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Pseudamnicola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7CA97D06A93960576B775C3B5825B10C" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Pseudamnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in the following, in parentheses), but theunique morphology of the penis, broad at the basis and tapered at the distal end (
<figureCitation id="D515DF93220379127008B9CEB05E2778" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Kaskakia khorrasanensis sp. n. a shell b penis in situ c-d penis (c: dorsal view, d: ventral view)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/20814" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Figs 10b-c</figureCitation>
), with a black pigmentation mark (vs. broad and elongated triangular penis), and the presence of broad cylindrical tentacles (slim cylindrical tentacles) will separate the new genus from 
<taxonomicName id="E494702F71ADA9F1F8488EA18D7B2EB8" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Pseudamnicola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EEAD6C2D59CDF72CE0572A0DBEE4A652" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Pseudamnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
